article.description:
Katie Douglas scored 17 points to lift the
Connecticut Sun to a 76-63 victory Wednesday over the Seattle Storm
before a sellout crowd of 10,891.
article.headline: Sun control tempo to earn victory against Storm
article.linkText: Sun steal win from Storm in front of sellout crowd
article.story:
SEATTLE -- Connecticut struggled with its shooting. The Sun
were still able to overcome a fatigued Seattle squad.

	   Katie Douglas scored 17 points, and the rested Sun used their
energy advantage to beat the Seattle Storm 76-63 on Wednesday
afternoon.

	   The Sun (8-11) had not played since Saturday in Los Angeles and
had waited for the Storm in Seattle the past two days. In the
meantime, the Storm played in Los Angeles Tuesday in a 82-47 rout
of the Sparks.

	   "The shot was not there, but the energy was still there. That
always helps," Connecticut Coach Mike Thibault said. "Seattle
might have been fatigued from their game [Tuesday] but you don't
feel sorry for them. If we have that little bit of extra energy you
have to use it to our advantage."

	   Nykesha Sales added 15 points and Evina Maltsi added 11 in the
balanced scoring for the Sun.

	   Lauren Jackson scored 24 points for the Storm (11-9), who had
won four of their previous five. Iziane Castro Marques added 13
points. Seattle played its fourth straight game without All-Star
guard Sue Bird, who is recovering from knee surgery last week.

	   "A lot of them [Storm players] didn't want to run with us
today" Sales said.

	   Storm coach Anne Donovan said back-to-back games "are
definitely difficult. With a game like tonight, I thought that we
didn't look too bad in there."

	   Earlier this month, Connecticut became the first WNBA team to
score at least 100 points in consecutive games. They shot franchise
record 63.9 percent their 110-89 victory over the Sparks Saturday.
They shot just 43 percent against the Storm.

	   "We were running up and down the same way," Thibault said,
"the ball just wasn't going in."

	   Douglas added, "That's what it's all about, controlling the
game. Anytime you have good energy from your five starters then you
can go to your bench and count on them to make contributions, good
things are going to happen to your team."

	   Connecticut's bench outscored Seattle's 20-2.

	   "That's a big difference in game like this," Thibault said.
"We're pretty balanced most of the time, but when Asjha Jones
[seven points] didn't have it, we went to other people. I felt our
bench had some big baskets."

	   Seattle, trailing by 12 late in the first half, came within
three points on a 14-footer by Wendy Palmer with 3:22 left in the
third quarter. But the Sun closed the quarter on a 12-5 run --
including a 3-pointer by Sales -- for a 61-51 lead.

	   The Storm pulled to 64-57 early in the fourth, but Connecticut
came up with three straight steals followed by fast-break points to
extend the lead.

	   "We would cut it to five then they would go on a run," Donovan
said. "We were in a hole by 10 at halftime and with a good team it
is very difficult to come back."

	   The Sun may be on facing fatigue themselves on Thursday playing
for the second straight day against Sacramento. The Storm, however,
now take six days off for All-Star break.

	   "There are a lot of factors that play into it, but we were
tired," Jackson said. "As a professional athlete we should be
used to this but fatigue definitely played a role."
